<subSubSection id="36D13C4583CEE9B56DFD14E5BAC16A1E" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="comments">
<paragraph id="8F095736439B412A05BFCA7553527849" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="14A6C5EAB73A2F0594CCD87EF29EC481" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Following the new ICN, 
<taxonomicName id="7F633FE0E33DDCDB5F179829BF1E0108" class="Pucciniomycetes" genus="Hemileia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hemileia smallii" order="Pucciniales" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="smallii">Hemileia smallii</taxonomicName>
has priority even though the type specimen includes only the asexual stage of this species. 
<bibRefCitation id="DA3F924345A010FDC2644C84ACB92153" author="Fernier, H" journalOrPublisher="Revue de mycolgie, Paris" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="58 - 63" title="Contribution a l'etude d'une Rouille de Strophanthus sarmentosus due a Hemileia smallii Wakef. et Hansford." volume="19" year="1954">Fernier (1954)</bibRefCitation>
described a name for the teleomorph using a different type specimen. Because he used the same epithet, that name is an illegitimate, later homonym. For this reason 
<bibRefCitation id="78B11E402ABDA69F02514444FC32023E" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Gjaerum et al. (2000)</bibRefCitation>
established another name for this species based on a different type specimen that is here regarded as a taxonomic synonym.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
